{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Froin's syndrome | image = Ependymoma.png | caption = [[Ependymoma]] of the [[Spinal cord|cervical spine]], completely obscurating the [[spinal canal]] | image_size = 160 px | pronounce = | field = | synonyms = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Froin's syndrome''' – coexistence of [[xanthochromia]], high protein level and marked [[coagulation]] of [[cerebrospinal fluid]] (CSF). It is caused by meningeal irritation (e.g. during [[meningitis|spinal meningitis]]) and CSF flow blockage by [[spinal tumor|tumour mass]] or [[abscess]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Govindarajan|first=R|author2=Khan, T|title=Froin's syndrome: an uncommon mimicker of Guillain–Barre syndrome.|journal=European Spine Journal|date=August 2012|volume=21|issue=8|pages=1674–5|pmid=22447409|doi=10.1007/s00586-012-2277-0|pmc=3535231}}</ref> Stagnation of the CSF within the [[thecal sac]] facilitates [[exudation]] from the tumour itself and activation of [[coagulation factor]]s. A clinical test formerly used for evaluation of [[spinal stenosis]] is [[Queckenstedt's maneuver]]. Nowadays, a [[magnetic resonance imaging]] is used for identification of CSF flow obstruction. It often shows the prolongation of [[Spin–lattice relaxation|T1]] and [[Spin–spin relaxation|T2 signal]] in CSF [[caudal (anatomical term)|caudal]] to a level of block.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mirza|first=S|author2=Adams, WM|author3=Corkhill, RA|title=Froin's syndrome revisited, 100 years on. Pseudo-Froin's syndrome on MRI.|journal=Clinical radiology|date=May 2008|volume=63|issue=5|pages=600–4|pmid=18374725|doi=10.1016/j.crad.2007.07.027}}</ref> This phenomenon is named after [[Georges Froin]] (1874–1932), a French physician who first described it.<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|1482|Froin's syndrome}}</ref><ref>Froin G. ''Inflammations méningées avec chromatique, fibrineuse et cytologique du liquide céphalo-rachidien''. Gazette des hôpitaux, Paris 1903; 76:1005–1006.</ref>
