'''Kuakini Medical Center''' is a private hospital in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]]. The center is run by the Kuakini Health System which also runs geriatric care facilities and a foundation.
==History== The organization started as the Japanese Benevolent Society in 1892 and was incorporated in 1899.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2001/12/07/news/story4.html|title=How Kuakini became an ‘American general hospital’: World War II forced a change in its focus away from reflecting Japanese culture|last=Altonn|first=Helen|date=December 7, 2001|website=archives.starbulletin.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-18}}</ref> The first Japanese Charity Hospital opened in 1900 and expanded in 1902. A larger facility was built in 1917 at the present site with donations from [[Emperor Taishō]] of Japan. In 1934 [[Emperor Hirohito]] of Japan donated funds for more expansion. After the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] in 1941, the US military occupied the hospital during [[World War II]] and renamed it Kuakini Medical Center, after the street.<ref>{{cite web |title= General Information: History |work= Kuakini Health System web site |url= http://www.kuakini.org/Kuakini/GeneralInfo/gen_History.asp |accessdate= November 23, 2010 }}</ref> The street was in turn named for [[John Adams Kuakini]] (1791–1844) who was acting [[Governor of Oahu]] in the 1830s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1042464|title=Place names of Hawaii|last=Pukui|first=Mary Kawena|last2=Elbert|first2=Samuel H.|last3=Mookini|first3=Esther T.|publisher=University Press of Hawaii|year=1974|isbn=082480208X|edition=Rev. and enl. ed|location=Honolulu|pages=|oclc=1042464|author-link=Mary Kawena Pukui|author-link2=Samuel Hoyt Elbert}}</ref>
